Subject: Re: [T2] Alcohol and Driving

At 08:53 PM 12/3/2001 -0500, Jim Mowreader wrote:
>David Bell sends:
>
> > Would it be possible to convert an air-cooled VW engine to run on 100%
> > ethanol? If it is possible, what would be involved? Would it work on carbs
> > or fuel injection, or both maybe? Change valve sizes, material,
> > lift/duartion, CR?  Hotter spark plugs? Anything else come to mind? Let's
> > assume that the supply of ethanol isn't a problem and that we're talking
> > about a small fleet, not a single vehicle.
>
>The following racing series run alcohol: the Indy Racing League (fuel
>injection, no turbos), CART (FI, turbo in 2001 changing to non-turbo in the
>next few years), World of Outlaws (carbs), Alcohol Funny Cars and Dragsters
>(not sure what they use for induction) and Monster Trucks (carbs with
>superchargers, IIRC). Monster trucks run alcohol because most monster truck
>races are held indoors, and alcohol exhaust is less likely to kill the
>spectators than gasoline exhaust. I'd say you could run either carb or FI.
>
>One thing I know you have to worry about is the construction of your
>induction system. Alcohol will dissolve parts of some carbs; get a copy of
>Stock Car Racing magazine and you'll find carbs specially set up for alcohol
>racing series. These won't dissolve. (These are also Holley 650cfm
>Dominators.




>  ..........Actually it is all the gaskets, diaphragms and seals in the 
> carburetor and fuel pump for that matter that would have to be changed to 
> a "Butyl" material for solvent resistance as will any fuel lines. Since 
> Alcohol is a Solvent it will "clean" out any thing it comes in contact 
> with so particles of dirt, rubber, carbon etc. will start traveling 
> through out your fuel system if everything is not replaced or pre cleaned 
> (this goes for metal fuel lines also). You will also have to put in 
> 25percent or more larger fuel jets as I believe alcohol/methanol/ethanol 
> is more oxygenated than gasoline, BUT the engine will run much 
> cooler.   And yes it does absorb water so if you leave any amount 
> contained for any time you will have to add a stabilizer/water 
> absorber.  About the fire hazard, back when the Indy 500 was run by USA 
> and all these cars carried up to 50-70 gallons of gas and hit a wall they 
> turned into incendiary bombs and the safety crews did not carry Halon or 
> Carbon Dioxide extinguishers just water which in turn spread the water. 
> So in 1963 or there abouts they changed to methanol which is not as 
> explosive and CAN be put out with water as it is not a petroleum product. 
> I saw this in two CART races this year as his pit crew (and the one next 
> to his) doused the driver (Christen Fittapaldi) with water. Now for other 
> reasons you do not want to pour water on the car as water tends to do 
> more harm after the fire is out. A good carbon dioxide (or foam) 
> extinguisher will smother the fire by displacing all the oxygen while not 
> destroying equipment.........  now I'm no expert...this is just my opinion.
>
